summary:
The Security Council, 
Recalling previous resolutions on the Israeli-Palestinian conflict, particularly resolutions 242, 338, 1397, and 1515, and the Madrid principles, 
Reiterating its vision of two democratic States, Israel and Palestine, living side by side in peace within secure and recognized borders, 
Welcoming the Quartet's statement and the Israeli-Palestinian Joint Understanding from Annapolis, 
Noting lasting peace requires mutual recognition, freedom from violence, and the two-State solution, 
Noting the 2002 Arab Peace Initiative, 
Encouraging the Quartet's work to support a comprehensive, just and lasting peace, 
1. Supports negotiations initiated at Annapolis in 2007 and commits to their irreversibility; 
2. Supports the parties' agreed principles and efforts to conclude a peace treaty resolving all outstanding issues; 
3. Calls on both parties to fulfil Roadmap obligations and refrain from undermining confidence or prejudicing negotiations; 
4. Calls on States and organizations to contribute to an atmosphere conducive to negotiations, support the Palestinian government, and assist in Palestinian economy and institution-building; 
5. Urges intensification of diplomatic efforts for mutual recognition and peaceful coexistence in the region; 
6. Welcomes the Quartet's consideration of an international meeting in Moscow in 2009; 
7. Decides to remain seized of the matter.
